Rating: 4
Sublime. I made this for friends on a frigid December evening and it was perfect. I doubled the veggies and herbs, used grass-fed beef, and instead of simmering it on top of the stove I cooked it covered in a 375 degree over for about two hours (I was using the oven for other things, so it was efficient); I reduced the liquid for about 20 minutes when it came out. The flavors were amazing--complex, a little fruity and sweet, rich. The meat was so tender but not falling apart. I served over egg fettucini with roast slices of Hubbard squash, a salad of greens, roast beets, and goat cheese, and crusty bread. Awesome winter meal, plates all wiped clean.

Rating: 4
I followed this recipe exactly - minus (unfortunately for me!) the cinnamon (hubby won't eat cinnamon) - so I 'compromised' by replacing about 1 cup of the water with beef stock. I used a Chilean cabernet sauvignon (a pleasantly well-balanced one, with a bit of spicy bite to it) and the meat turned out full-flavoured and extremely good. I wasn't sure exactly how small to chop the veggies (in the picture, you don't see 'chunks' of veggies) so I chose to work with a medium dice. Turned out to be the right choice, as the veggies kind of meld into the sauce, creating a rich, thick gravy. I served it with a potato purée mixed with a bit of sour cream and feta cheese, Thomas Keller's Leek Bread Pudding (also part of this article; recipe on this site), and some roasted grapes (red, green and blue varieties) with halved shallots and thyme. A very memorable meal!